          "body": "David's speech in verses 12-13 is the chapter's moral and spiritual center. The command in verse 12 is followed immediately by the confession of verse 13: 'Because you did not carry it at the first, the LORD our God made an outburst on us, for we did not seek Him according to the ordinance.' Two features of this confession demand attention. First, David uses 'we' — not 'you failed' but 'we did not seek.' The king owns the communal failure. Second, the word *darash* (seek) in verse 13 is one of the Chronicler's most loaded theological terms; it appears throughout Chronicles as the mark of a king who will prosper (1 Chronicles 10:13-14; 2 Chronicles 7:14). The failure was not merely procedural — it was a failure to seek God at all. David had sought Israel's approval (13:2) but had not sought God's prescription. The corrective is therefore not merely procedural either: 'consecrate yourselves' (v. 12) precedes the carrying. Personal holiness must precede the handling of holy things."
