          "body": "Verses 16-24 slow the narrative to catalog every musician, instrument, and assignment. Heman, Asaph, and Ethan are appointed as the three chief singers (v. 17) — figures whose names will dominate the Psalter (Psalms 73-83 are Asaph's; Psalm 88-89 are Ethan's and Heman's). Three instrumental registers are assigned: bronze cymbals for the three chiefs (v. 19), harps tuned to alamoth for eight players (v. 20), lyres tuned to the sheminith for six (v. 21). Chenaniah directs the whole because he is 'skilled' (bin, v. 22) — a word meaning to understand, discern, have insight. The Chronicler does not romanticize Spirit-led spontaneity; he presents competence as the qualification for appointment. What this section establishes for the Chronicler's post-exilic audience is a charter: the guild-structure of the temple musicians is not Solomon's invention or Ezra's innovation — it goes back to David, who received it from God. The music is as much a prescribed element of worship as the Levitical carrying."
