        "title": "The procession and its shadow — all Israel's joy and Michal's contempt",
        "range": "15:25-29",
        "excerpt": "Thus all Israel brought up the ark of the covenant of the LORD with shouting, and with sound of the horn, with trumpets, with loud-sounding cymbals, with harps and lyres.",
        "body": "The procession of verses 25-28 is the chapter's doxological payoff. Every preparation (vv. 1-15) and every musical assignment (vv. 16-24) has been building to the moment when 'all Israel' — David, the elders, the commanders of thousands — move together with the ark from Obed-edom's house to the City of David. The Chronicler names seven acoustic elements: shouting (*teruah*), ram's horn (*shophar*), trumpets (*chatsotserah*), cymbals, harps, lyres. The effect is deliberately overwhelming — the arrival of God's covenant throne in His chosen city is not a quiet moment.\n\nVerse 26 is the chapter's theological surprise. God does not merely permit the correctly-ordered procession; He actively *helps* the Levites who are carrying the ark. The verb *azar* (help, assist) is the word used of God's military assistance to Israel in battle; here it is applied to liturgical transport. The implication is striking: when the worship is rightly ordered, God participates in its performance. He is not a passive recipient of correctly-executed ritual; He is an active co-participant with those who seek Him according to His ordinance. The sacrifice of seven bulls and seven rams — offered because of His help, not to secure it — responds to divine assistance already experienced.\n\nDavid's linen ephod (v. 27) is the chapter's sharpest image. A king wearing priestly garb is a deliberate subordination of political identity to sacral function. David does not lead this procession as Israel's military commander; he leads it as Israel's chief worshiper, dressed in the same linen as the Levites themselves. 2 Samuel 6:14 uses the same detail, and both accounts intend the same point: David's greatness is measured not by his throne but by his willingness to humble himself before the ark. He is not embarrassed by the dancing or the ephod; his identity on this day is defined by his posture before God, not his position over people.\n\nMichal's contempt in verse 29 is the chapter's final, devastating note. She is identified as 'the daughter of Saul' — not 'the wife of David' or 'the queen.' Her identity is Saulide, not Davidic. The Chronicler does not reproduce the confrontation of 2 Samuel 6:20-23, where Michal accuses David of uncovering himself before slave girls and David defends his worship before the Lord who chose him over her father's house. He leaves only the contempt — and its location in her *heart*. The heart (*lev*) is the Chronicler's standard location for spiritual disposition (2 Chronicles 7:14; 12:14; 15:15). A heart of contempt before the worship of God is the antithesis of the consecrated, joyful, humble heart that has characterized every participant in the chapter's procession. Michal is the shadow that makes the chapter's light visible — the one who refused to descend from the window into the street, to exchange the daughter-of-Saul identity for the identity of the worshiper.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Teruah* (shouting, v. 28) — the liturgical war-shout of Yahweh's people; used of the Sinai theophany (Exodus 19:16), of Jericho (Joshua 6:5), and of temple worship (Psalm 47:5). *Azar* (helped, v. 26) — divine military assistance applied to liturgical act; the same verb appears in 1 Chronicles 12:18 of God's spirit rushing on Amasai. *Bazah* (despised, v. 29) — to treat as contemptible, to regard with disdain; the same root used of Esau despising his birthright (Genesis 25:34) — the squandering of something sacred through failure to value it."
